<?xml version="1.0"?><eml:eml xmlns:eml="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.0.0" xmlns:stmml="http://www.xml-cml.org/schema/stmml" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xmlns:ds="eml://ecoinformatics.org/dataset-2.0.0" packageId="knb.116.1" system="knb" xsi:schemaLocation="eml://ecoinformatics.org/eml-2.0.0 eml.xsd" scope="system"><!--Person who filled in the catalog entry form: Jin-Song Chen--><!--Form filled out at Tue Sep 28 23:48:57 2004 GMT--><dataset scope="document"><alternateIdentifier system="USDA/ARS GrazingLands Research Lab">hfa1907</alternateIdentifier><title>ARS SHAWMS DATA FOR SGP97, Little Washita, OK</title><creator scope="document"><organizationName>USDA/ARS GrazingLands Research Lab</organizationName></creator><creator scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Patrick</givenName><surName>Starks</surName></individualName><organizationName>USDA/ARS GrazingLands Research Lab</organizationName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>7207 W. Cheyenne. St.</deliveryPoint><city>El Reno</city><administrativeArea>Oklahoma</administrativeArea><postalCode>73036</postalCode><country>USA</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">405-262-5291</phone><electronicMailAddress>pstarks@grl.ars.usda.gov</electronicMailAddress></creator><metadataProvider scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Jin-Song</givenName><surName>Chen</surName></individualName></metadataProvider><abstract><para>The soil water matric potential data described herein are contributed by the Agricultural Research Service, Grazinglands Research Laboratory, El Reno, OK. The data for SGP97 period (June and July) is provided for the ARS SHAWMS stations in the Little Washita River Watershed. The data consists of matric potential values at 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, and 60 cm below ground surface, and is provided in 1-hour increments.</para></abstract><additionalInfo><para>This metadata registry was entered by Jin-Song Chen during the KNB Data Management Tools Workshop in Santa Barbara, California, Sept. 27-30, 2004, sponsored by NCEAS.</para></additionalInfo><intellectualRights><para>no restrictions</para></intellectualRights><distribution scope="document"><online><url function="download">ftp://164.58.150.49/pub/sgp97/SHAWMS/</url></online></distribution><distribution scope="document"><offline><mediumName>digital</mediumName></offline></distribution><coverage scope="document"><temporalCoverage scope="document"><rangeOfDates><beginDate><calendarDate>1997-01-01</calendarDate></beginDate><endDate><calendarDate>1997-01-01</calendarDate></endDate></rangeOfDates></temporalCoverage><geographicCoverage scope="document"><geographicDescription>Little Washita, OKlahoma</geographicDescription><boundingCoordinates><westBoundingCoordinate>-98.2928</westBoundingCoordinate><eastBoundingCoordinate>-97.2928</eastBoundingCoordinate><northBoundingCoordinate>34.9367</northBoundingCoordinate><southBoundingCoordinate>34.7967</southBoundingCoordinate></boundingCoordinates></geographicCoverage></coverage><contact scope="document"><individualName><givenName>Patrick</givenName><surName>Starks</surName></individualName><organizationName>USDA/ARS GrazingLands Research Lab</organizationName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>7207 W. Cheyenne. St.</deliveryPoint><city>El Reno</city><administrativeArea>Oklahoma</administrativeArea><postalCode>73036</postalCode><country>USA</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">405-262-5291</phone><electronicMailAddress>pstarks@grl.ars.usda.gov</electronicMailAddress></contact><methods><methodStep><description><section><title>Automatic Soil Heat And Water Measurement  using soil heat dissipation sensor</title><para>Soil Heat And Water Measurement System: The soil water sensor incorporated into the SHAWMS is Campbell Scientific&#146;s Model 229-L soil heat dissipation sensor. This sensor is designed to provide measurements of soil matric potential (a measure of how tightly the soil holds water); therefore, knowledge of a particular soil&#146;s soil water retention curve is required for conversion of matric potential into volumetric water content. The sensor was evaluated by Reece (1996) and found to give reliable estimates of matric potential between -10 J/kg and -1200 J/kg (0.1 bar to 12 bar), inclusive. Briefly, the 229-L consists of a small, hollow, stainless steel tube inserted into a porous ceramic matrix. The stainless steel tube contains a miniature heater and thermocouple. An initial soil temperature is taken with the sensor, then the sensor is heated for 21 seconds and an ending soil temperature reading is made. A del T value is calculated from the initial and ending soil temperature readings. del T is inversely related to soil water matric potential, and the del T soil matric potential relationship is typically ascertained via sensor calibration.</para></section></description></methodStep><sampling><studyExtent><description><para>Data collection started on 6/1/1997 and ended on 7/31/1997</para></description></studyExtent><samplingDescription><para>Sensor deployment: There are 8 229-Ls per SHAWM site. 3 sensors are located at 5 cm below the soil surface (noted as 5a, 5b, 5c), and 1 each at 10, 15, 20, 25, and 60 cm below the surface.</para></samplingDescription></sampling></methods><access authSystem="knb" order="denyFirst" scope="document"><allow><principal>uid=knbadmin,o=NCEAS,dc=ecoinformatics,dc=org</principal><permission>all</permission></allow><allow><principal>uid=jschen,o=unaffiliated,dc=ecoinformatics,dc=org</principal><permission>all</permission></allow><allow><principal>public</principal><permission>read</permission></allow></access></dataset></eml:eml>